123
00:07:08.952 --> 00:07:12.512
And if I stratify that weighted average, that 20%, and I

124
00:07:13.232 --> 00:07:16.652
told you the global uptake in countries that have limited

125
00:07:16.692 --> 00:07:19.182
resources, it would be closer to about 9%.

126
00:07:19.812 --> 00:07:23.312
It just wasn't reaching where it needed to get to.

127
00:07:24.592 --> 00:07:27.852
So I'm going to talk a little bit about my research today, as well as some of the

128
00:07:27.892 --> 00:07:31.492
other research that's informed policy and important

129
00:07:31.512 --> 00:07:34.472
discoveries. So my research is very focused.

130
00:07:34.592 --> 00:07:37.272
How do we control then eliminate HPV-driven cancers?

131
00:07:37.392 --> 00:07:41.272
I am all HPV all the time. I do primary prevention work with

132
00:07:41.412 --> 00:07:45.392
HPV-driven cancers through prophylactic HPV vaccination

133
00:07:45.412 --> 00:07:47.472
with a special focus on single-dose.

134
00:07:47.572 --> 00:07:51.022
I also do etiology and secondary prevention work, but today, I'm going to focus on

135
00:07:51.172 --> 00:07:53.622
HPV vaccination for cervical cancer prevention.

136
00:07:55.452 --> 00:07:57.532
So prior to my time at the NCI,

137
00:07:58.602 --> 00:08:02.522
before the HPV vaccines were licensed, there were two

138
00:08:02.532 --> 00:08:06.292
pharmaceutical companies moving forward with large Phase III clinical trials,

139
00:08:06.742 --> 00:08:10.582
and the NCI said, "You know what? There needs to be a publicly funded trial as

140
00:08:10.632 --> 00:08:14.432
well. We need to have access to data to know what's going on." And so the NCI

141
00:08:14.472 --> 00:08:18.272
launched a Costa Rica HPV vaccine trial, which we refer to as CVT,

142
00:08:18.452 --> 00:08:21.532
in 2004. It was a pre-licensure trial

143
00:08:21.852 --> 00:08:25.532
investigating the safety and the efficacy of three doses

144
00:08:25.792 --> 00:08:27.712
of the bivalent HPV vaccine.

145
00:08:28.892 --> 00:08:32.592
In 2004 and 2005, they enrolled nearly 7,500 women

146
00:08:33.052 --> 00:08:35.692
between the ages of 18 and 25 years.

147
00:08:36.192 --> 00:08:40.153
They were randomized to receive either three doses of a HepA vaccine as a

148
00:08:40.172 --> 00:08:44.033
control vaccine or the Cervarix GSK bivalent vaccine.

149
00:08:44.952 --> 00:08:48.812
Because these women were 18 to 25 years old, because this was in

150
00:08:48.832 --> 00:08:52.692
a pre-licensure trial where we were evaluating safety and efficacy,

151
00:08:53.372 --> 00:08:57.281
20% of participants received fewer than three doses.

152
00:08:57.872 --> 00:09:00.012
Leading reasons for this, they were getting pregnant.

153
00:09:00.072 --> 00:09:01.832
We didn't vaccinate during pregnancy.

154
00:09:01.841 --> 00:09:05.832
They had a referral to colposcopy, so that put them on a different track.

155
00:09:06.292 --> 00:09:09.972
So we then had a group of people who received one and two doses.

156
00:09:11.452 --> 00:09:14.352
In 2011, we published our initial data.

157
00:09:14.452 --> 00:09:17.452
We said four years after HPV vaccination, we had

158
00:09:17.552 --> 00:09:21.332
non-randomized analysis that suggested that one dose

159
00:09:21.372 --> 00:09:24.132
appeared to protect as well as three doses.

160
00:09:24.192 --> 00:09:27.932
We were very excited with this, but it completely broke with vaccine

161
00:09:27.992 --> 00:09:31.932
dogma. Vaccine dogma said that subunit vaccines,

162
00:09:32.052 --> 00:09:34.952
so vaccines that are predicated on one part of the

163
00:09:36.912 --> 00:09:40.712
virus, in this case, the virus capsid, requires

164
00:09:40.772 --> 00:09:44.172
prime plus boost to induce protective immunity.

165
00:09:44.372 --> 00:09:47.922
So we said, "Everyone, this is hypothesis-generating." It

166
00:09:48.432 --> 00:09:51.312
was not received very well, and we got a lot of pushback.

167
00:09:51.392 --> 00:09:55.332
We had to really commit to generating the data, and in fact, there was a

168
00:09:55.372 --> 00:09:58.962
piece in "The New Yorker" this year that says, "Kramer was subjected to God knows

169
00:09:59.012 --> 00:10:02.872
how much skepticism," said the Dame Margaret Stanley, who I

170
00:10:02.932 --> 00:10:06.292
adore, of course. She counted herself among the

171
00:10:06.352 --> 00:10:10.272
disbelievers back then. She said it was heresy for a

172
00:10:10.312 --> 00:10:13.092
protein-based vaccine to work with only one dose.

173
00:10:13.132 --> 00:10:16.872
So this is where I pause in my talk and I say, "Stay true to the

174
00:10:16.912 --> 00:10:20.911
data." We have to just continue to let the data drive our course of

175
00:10:20.952 --> 00:10:22.652
inquiry. So we kept going.

176
00:10:23.471 --> 00:10:27.112
In 2013, we published our antibody data, and we showed

177
00:10:27.192 --> 00:10:31.022
stable antibody responses for four years following one dose of

178
00:10:31.112 --> 00:10:34.872
the vaccine, and we said, "Oh my gosh, it's durable." And then we

179
00:10:34.892 --> 00:10:38.352
needed more data because, again, we still were meeting with such disbelief.

180
00:10:38.432 --> 00:10:39.812
So we reached out to the industry

181
00:10:41.292 --> 00:10:44.612
who had run these Phase III trials, and we said, "Can we work in your datasets?"

182
00:10:45.312 --> 00:10:48.732
GSK said yes, and we reproduced similar single-dose

183
00:10:48.912 --> 00:10:52.672
HPV vaccine efficacy results in their PATRICIA trial, and we said, "Oh my

184
00:10:52.732 --> 00:10:56.512
goodness, it's consistent." So what happened next, and why was it needed?

185
00:10:57.332 --> 00:11:01.132
We continued to generate data on single dose in this original trial, and I'm going

186
00:11:01.152 --> 00:11:04.592
to share some of those data now. And we and others embark on

187
00:11:04.812 --> 00:11:08.392
formal randomized clinical trials to evaluate one-dose HPV

188
00:11:08.452 --> 00:11:09.252
vaccination.

189
00:11:10.932 --> 00:11:14.432
So this is a cut of our data 11 years after

190
00:11:14.592 --> 00:11:18.052
HPV vaccination in this non-randomized one-dose group,

191
00:11:18.612 --> 00:11:22.402
and we're benchmarking our one-dose arm against the women who received three

192
00:11:22.472 --> 00:11:25.572
doses. And so this is against HPV 16,

193
00:11:25.652 --> 00:11:29.292
18 infections,

194
00:11:29.712 --> 00:11:33.252
and the vaccine efficacy, as you can see, is quite the same.

195
00:11:33.852 --> 00:11:36.732
So why isn't this enough? Why can't we just say, "Let's change policy.

196
00:11:36.862 --> 00:11:40.832
Let's do one dose." Well, two points. One, non-randomized.

197
00:11:40.872 --> 00:11:44.671
It's non-randomized. We did everything in the world to rule out selection bias, but

198
00:11:44.732 --> 00:11:47.412
we can't overcome non-randomized.

199
00:11:47.432 --> 00:11:49.152
And also, our one-dose group was small.

200
00:11:49.192 --> 00:11:51.352
It had 112 people in it,

201
00:11:52.212 --> 00:11:56.092
so it wasn't powered. We were limited just by the number of people who went off

202
00:11:56.192 --> 00:11:59.872
schedule and got one dose. So we also did

203
00:11:59.892 --> 00:12:02.952
antibody work in these people. This is the same group of people.

204
00:12:03.552 --> 00:12:06.512
So on this figure, I'm showing you follow up to year

205
00:12:06.552 --> 00:12:10.416
11.And then on a log scale, the HPV

206
00:12:10.436 --> 00:12:14.416
16 antibody GMCs, and the data for HPV

207
00:12:14.436 --> 00:12:15.276
18 looks the same.

208
00:12:16.736 --> 00:12:20.416
Starting with the three-dose arm here in purple, what you see is this peak

209
00:12:20.456 --> 00:12:24.316
here that starting kind of higher up, and then it goes into this plateau,

210
00:12:24.436 --> 00:12:28.336
and the plateau keeps going. What has been really remarkably

211
00:12:28.396 --> 00:12:31.896
surprising is that for the one dose, we see durable

212
00:12:33.136 --> 00:12:35.236
protection that is also sustaining.

213
00:12:35.316 --> 00:12:39.116
And in fact, if we look at the difference between the one-dose antibody

214
00:12:39.156 --> 00:12:41.676
levels and the three dose, it's about four-fold.

215
00:12:42.696 --> 00:12:46.636
Virology immunology, not my expertise, but if we look at the

216
00:12:46.696 --> 00:12:50.606
experts in the room, especially John Schiller, who's sitting with us, he would

217
00:12:50.636 --> 00:12:53.916
say, I think, that a four-fold difference in

218
00:12:53.996 --> 00:12:57.396
antibodies is not usually a break point for where you see

219
00:12:57.416 --> 00:13:01.316
protection and not protection. And in fact, in the efficacy

220
00:13:01.356 --> 00:13:05.096
data I showed you in the previous slide, we're seeing robust efficacy no

221
00:13:05.176 --> 00:13:07.136
matter what the antibody level is.

222
00:13:07.596 --> 00:13:11.496
So this kind of gives us a little nugget of information where even though we

223
00:13:11.516 --> 00:13:15.296
lack a correlate of protection, we do observe that lower antibody levels do

224
00:13:15.456 --> 00:13:18.896
not equate to inferior protection. This is in the field.

225
00:13:18.976 --> 00:13:20.736
We just wrapped up the 20-year visit,

226
00:13:21.956 --> 00:13:25.646
and our 20-year results are actually expected towards the end of this year.

227
00:13:25.916 --> 00:13:29.716
So that's quite exciting. So as I said,

228
00:13:29.936 --> 00:13:33.576
we and others knew we needed more. We need formal randomized trial.

229
00:13:33.776 --> 00:13:37.656
And so we launched two. We had ESCUDO, which is a formal non-inferiority

230
00:13:37.666 --> 00:13:41.626
trial of one to two doses. And then we had PRISMA, which is

231
00:13:41.676 --> 00:13:44.856
a one-dose efficacy trial in young adult women.

232
00:13:44.866 --> 00:13:47.956
And I'm going to talk a little bit about both of those today after I check the

233
00:13:47.996 --> 00:13:48.236
time.

234
00:13:50.236 --> 00:13:53.976
Seems good. Okay. So ESCUDO. ESCUDO had co-primary

235
00:13:54.056 --> 00:13:57.766
aims. The first one was the non-inferiority of one versus two doses in the

236
00:13:57.796 --> 00:14:01.056
prevention of new cervical HPV 16/18

237
00:14:01.096 --> 00:14:04.976
infections in girls who were 12 to 16

238
00:14:04.996 --> 00:14:08.456
years. So this recruited 20,000

239
00:14:08.556 --> 00:14:12.136
girls at enrollment were randomized to vaccine product.

240
00:14:12.176 --> 00:14:16.156
We studied both the bivalent vaccine and the Merck nonavalent vaccine.

241
00:14:16.676 --> 00:14:19.336
Six months later, they were randomized to a dosing schedule.

242
00:14:19.536 --> 00:14:23.496
They either received a second dose of the same vaccine or a control vaccine if they

243
00:14:23.516 --> 00:14:25.256
