244
00:14:26.396 --> 00:14:30.196
We actively followed them over six-month intervals to collect cervical

245
00:14:30.316 --> 00:14:34.116
cells, blood, and urine. And you can see this went out to

246
00:14:34.156 --> 00:14:38.136
five years. A note that our girls aged into the cervical

247
00:14:38.196 --> 00:14:41.216
sample self-collection at the age of 15.

248
00:14:41.256 --> 00:14:43.516
Prior to that, we assume they were HPV negative.

249
00:14:45.176 --> 00:14:47.556
So here are the results. We published these in December.

250
00:14:47.676 --> 00:14:51.536
These are for the first co-primary aim, looking at the non-inferiority of

251
00:14:51.576 --> 00:14:52.936
one versus two doses.

252
00:14:53.956 --> 00:14:57.556
For this endpoint of incident, six-month persistent cervical HPV

253
00:14:57.576 --> 00:15:01.216
16 infections and who were HPV naive during the

254
00:15:01.236 --> 00:15:04.676
vaccination phase. So I'm going to walk you through this table.

255
00:15:04.936 --> 00:15:07.736
I've had to learn quite a bit about non-inferiority trials.

256
00:15:08.316 --> 00:15:10.496
Efficacy is much easier to consume.

257
00:15:11.476 --> 00:15:14.316
This is the Cervarix arm and then the Gardasil 9 arm,

258
00:15:15.256 --> 00:15:18.396
the one dose and the two dose. You see the number per arm,

259
00:15:19.296 --> 00:15:23.016
the number of events in each arm, and then the cumulative event

260
00:15:23.116 --> 00:15:26.996
rate, and a rate difference on an absolute scale.

261
00:15:28.016 --> 00:15:31.816
You then see a P-value that's testing whether

262
00:15:31.876 --> 00:15:35.636
this observed rate difference rules out a pre-specified

263
00:15:35.736 --> 00:15:39.056
margin that maps to at least 80% efficacy.

264
00:15:39.716 --> 00:15:43.356
So for the Cervarix arm, you see a very small rate

265
00:15:43.416 --> 00:15:47.336
difference with a highly statistically significant P-value, which means

266
00:15:47.416 --> 00:15:50.666
that we're observing here over 80% efficacy, which was the

267
00:15:50.696 --> 00:15:52.796
non-inferiority margin of the trial.

268
00:15:52.836 --> 00:15:56.796
When we go to Gardasil 9, again, for an endpoint of 16/18,

269
00:15:57.256 --> 00:16:00.856
we again see a very small rate difference and a highly statistically significant

270
00:16:00.936 --> 00:16:03.915
P-value, so we succeeded on co-primary aim one.

271
00:16:06.356 --> 00:16:10.116
We additionally conducted an end-of-study survey to capture

272
00:16:10.136 --> 00:16:14.116
data on unvaccinated women. We could not run this ethically in

273
00:16:14.156 --> 00:16:18.016
our opinion as a randomized control trial against a zero-dose group because

274
00:16:18.096 --> 00:16:19.796
these vaccines were already approved.

275
00:16:19.836 --> 00:16:23.496
We really thought the question at hand was compared to the gold standard dosing

276
00:16:23.576 --> 00:16:25.116
regimen, how does one dose compare?

277
00:16:25.576 --> 00:16:28.156
But we did want that zero-dose information.

278
00:16:28.216 --> 00:16:30.216
We enrolled a survey who

279
00:16:31.156 --> 00:16:33.496
looked very similar in terms of age and region to the

280
00:16:33.516 --> 00:16:36.936
randomized clinical group. We

281
00:16:37.116 --> 00:16:40.996
captured their HPV infection status, and then we provided them HPV

282
00:16:41.036 --> 00:16:41.856
vaccination.

283
00:16:42.836 --> 00:16:46.476
With these data, we were able to compute HPV vaccine efficacy.

284
00:16:46.656 --> 00:16:50.636
So here we're seeing against that unvaccinated survey efficacy

285
00:16:50.676 --> 00:16:54.656
for one dose Cervarix, two doses Cervarix, one dose Gardasil 9, and two doses

286
00:16:54.676 --> 00:16:57.936
Gardasil 9, and what you see is very,

287
00:16:58.496 --> 00:17:02.236
very high protection for all four arms with no

288
00:17:02.276 --> 00:17:02.976
differences.

289
00:17:05.436 --> 00:17:07.836
We do have additional data that I'm not going to share today.

290
00:17:08.436 --> 00:17:12.356
Looking at the other five carcinogenic types

291
00:17:12.396 --> 00:17:16.176
in the nonavalent vaccine were looked at as a pre-specified aim.

292
00:17:16.216 --> 00:17:20.116
We also saw no significant differences between one and two doses on

293
00:17:20.176 --> 00:17:23.955
that. And if I refer you to the paper, we do everything

294
00:17:24.017 --> 00:17:27.936
under the sun, every individual genotype, every composite endpoint, so

295
00:17:28.116 --> 00:17:31.796
lots of information there, one million supplemental tables.

296
00:17:32.896 --> 00:17:35.536
Here is one of our secondary aims, which is immunogenicity.

297
00:17:35.636 --> 00:17:37.696
These data are not yet published.

298
00:17:38.496 --> 00:17:42.436
They're under review right now. So our immunogenicity

299
00:17:42.456 --> 00:17:46.396
data went out to three years. If we look at this legend, you see Cervarix

300
00:17:46.436 --> 00:17:50.276
is blue, Gardasil 9 is red. If it's a solid

301
00:17:50.356 --> 00:17:53.896
dot, it's a one dose and an open dot, it's two

302
00:17:53.956 --> 00:17:57.896
doses. So the antibody patterns fell out kind of what you

303
00:17:57.916 --> 00:18:01.436
would expect. Three years later, what you see is two

304
00:18:01.496 --> 00:18:05.456
doses of Cervarix gives the highest, then two doses of Gardasil

305
00:18:05.776 --> 00:18:08.196
9, then one dose of Cervarix, and one dose of Gardasil 9.

306
00:18:08.876 --> 00:18:10.396
Similar for HPV 18.

307
00:18:11.836 --> 00:18:15.476
And for all the types that are included in a vaccine

308
00:18:15.576 --> 00:18:17.736
formulation, you see really robust antibody

309
00:18:17.816 --> 00:18:21.540
patterns.So, as I had indicated,

310
00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:25.480
several groups around the world started

311
00:18:25.540 --> 00:18:29.300
launching single-dose trials. I would like to just touch on a couple of

312
00:18:29.360 --> 00:18:33.260
them. I do put the references in the bottom right corner if

313
00:18:33.300 --> 00:18:36.490
you want more information. Trials were launched in

314
00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:39.920
Kenya, the KENCHI trial. This one is critically

315
00:18:39.930 --> 00:18:43.750
important as it changed global policy.

316
00:18:44.260 --> 00:18:45.470
It was randomized

317
00:18:46.300 --> 00:18:49.440
women aged 15 to 20 with a three-year follow-up.

318
00:18:49.480 --> 00:18:52.560
They looked at also the GSK vaccine and the nonavalent

319
00:18:52.639 --> 00:18:56.320
vaccine and showed high vaccine efficacy

320
00:18:56.380 --> 00:18:59.940
against HPV 16/18 for both vaccines.

321
00:19:00.560 --> 00:19:04.300
Many of us were following the GSK vaccine and

322
00:19:04.340 --> 00:19:08.260
the alum-adjuvanted vaccines because there was a real question when

323
00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:10.440
we started these single-dose trials about,

324
00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:14.580
the GSK vaccines have a different sort of

325
00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:17.200
adjuvant that gives a higher antibody response.

326
00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:21.180
We saw that in the previous immunogenicity slides, and so we had a real

327
00:19:21.260 --> 00:19:24.780
question if that was going to be necessary to confer

328
00:19:24.820 --> 00:19:28.690
protection with a single dose. And in fact, what we're seeing now is,

329
00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:32.700
in fact, all the Merck vaccines that have an alum adjuvant, the

330
00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:34.560
GSK vaccines that have a TLR

331
00:19:36.420 --> 00:19:39.820
agonist adjuvant, are all giving similarly robust

332
00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:40.970
results.

333
00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:44.130
Tanzania launched an immunogenicity study.

334
00:19:45.120 --> 00:19:47.360
High seropositivity for one dose.

335
00:19:48.540 --> 00:19:52.040
And India also had a broken randomization

336
00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:55.560
trial, like CVT, where we had these non-randomized women,

337
00:19:56.140 --> 00:19:59.320
and they have a huge one-dose group of about 5,000

338
00:19:59.390 --> 00:20:03.150
women. Follow-up time out is 12 years now, going

339
00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:07.180
strong with follow-up. Not only are they showing high vaccine efficacy

340
00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:10.720
against virologic endpoints, but they're also providing evidence against

341
00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:12.200
histologic endpoints.

342
00:20:13.900 --> 00:20:16.220
There do remain persistent gaps in knowledge.

343
00:20:16.300 --> 00:20:18.460
I'm not here just to do all the sunshine.

344
00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:20.580
I have to do the clouds, too.

345
00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:25.720
We need to know how far up an age scale one dose can work.

346
00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:29.940
Is it adult women? We have very little data on men,

347
00:20:30.390 --> 00:20:34.360
though the a priori biological hypothesis is that it

348
00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:37.520
will work well at mucosal sites in men.

349
00:20:37.840 --> 00:20:40.180
We don't know about non-cervical sites, oral and anal.

350
00:20:40.230 --> 00:20:43.500
And I showed you in the USA, oropharynx cancer is really important.

351
00:20:44.420 --> 00:20:47.380
And new vaccine products are coming out. This is amazing.

352
00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:50.100
It's exactly what a healthy vaccine market needs.

353
00:20:50.180 --> 00:20:52.380
We see new products coming out of China and India.

354
00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:57.080
We have optimistic data showing that one dose will work there, but we'll

355
00:20:57.140 --> 00:20:58.720
need to continue to follow that as well.

356
00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:03.640
I do want to wrap up with two more points.

357
00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:07.720
One, we have another trial that I had mentioned, our PRISMA

358
00:21:07.800 --> 00:21:11.720
trial. This is single-dose HPV vaccine protection among

359
00:21:11.760 --> 00:21:15.650
adult women aged 18 to 30. So I shared some of the gaps that

360
00:21:15.700 --> 00:21:18.710
are in the literature right now, and now I'm going to tell you a little bit about

361
00:21:18.740 --> 00:21:22.640
what we're trying to do to work in some of those spaces.

362
00:21:23.380 --> 00:21:27.320
What is the point of getting vaccination, thinking in these

363
00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:31.380
resource-limited settings in women 18 to 30, where perhaps

364
00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:32.080
standing up

365
00:21:33.200 --> 00:21:36.260
screening has been an overwhelming challenge?

366
00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:40.380
We hope to accelerate the potential impact of HPV

367
00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:44.270
vaccination. So right now, if we vaccinate 12 to 16-year-olds or

368
00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:48.420
9 to 15-year-olds, we are waiting decades to see the reduction in

369
00:21:48.460 --> 00:21:52.260
cervical cancers, and we want to bring that forward in calendar time.

370
00:21:52.680 --> 00:21:56.500
And so one of our approaches to doing that is to vaccinate

371
00:21:56.520 --> 00:21:59.760
further up on age range. This could be considered like a catch-up,

372
00:22:00.460 --> 00:22:03.360
programmatically a catch-up. We're not leaving it there forever.

373
00:22:03.440 --> 00:22:06.860
It's a one-time thing. It's a band-aid while we wait for the

374
00:22:06.940 --> 00:22:10.780
vaccinated cohorts to age into cancer-susceptible years.

375
00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:15.380
We did an enrollment visit in 2022, over 5,000 women, and then

376
00:22:15.440 --> 00:22:17.640
three months later, a vaccination visit.

377
00:22:18.340 --> 00:22:22.260
At those two visits, we collect a cervical sample to rule out prevalent HPV

378
00:22:22.300 --> 00:22:25.360
infection to form an ATP cohort. We then

379
00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:29.930
randomize in a blinded fashion to one dose of the nonavalent, one dose of the

380
00:22:29.980 --> 00:22:32.200
bivalent, and one dose of a control vaccine.

381
00:22:32.620 --> 00:22:34.540
Our follow-up started at 12 months.

382
00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:37.039
We then saw them every six months for three years.

383
00:22:37.580 --> 00:22:41.340
Cervical HPV virologic endpoint is our primary endpoint,

384
00:22:41.800 --> 00:22:45.340
but we do have anal and oral cell collections

385
00:22:45.740 --> 00:22:49.520
to inform a secondary endpoint. So again, I told you persistent gaps in the

386
00:22:49.600 --> 00:22:52.720
literature included, does one dose protect at these

387
00:22:52.820 --> 00:22:56.780
non-cervical sites? The biologic hypothesis is yes,

388
00:22:56.840 --> 00:22:59.300
it will, but we need data to inform that.

389
00:23:00.480 --> 00:23:04.100
Very exciting news. Our results are expected in fall of this

390
00:23:04.220 --> 00:23:07.120
year. We look to break them over the summer.

391
00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:09.980
We're working really hard. We're tired.

